5000|$|Although the {{governor}} requested Federal troops {{to curb the}} violence, President Ulysses S. Grant hesitated to act. He feared being accused of [...] "bayonet rule" [...] — which he believed would undoubtedly be exploited by Democrats to carry Ohio in that year's state elections. The violence went unchecked and the plan worked as intended: during Mississippi's 1875 statewide election, five counties with large black <b>majorities</b> <b>polled</b> only 12, 7, 4, 2, and 0 Republican votes, respectively. The Republican dominance of 30,000 votes in the 1874 national and city elections was reversed in 1875 to a Democratic majority of 30,000 in statewide elections.|$|R
